  "description": "¶Entry conditions Use functors only when you already have:\nTwo categories with explicit objects and morphisms. A way to map objects to objects and morphisms to morphisms. Proof that identities and composition are preserved. ¶Definitions A functor F:C→DF:C \\to D maps objects of CC to objects of DD and morphisms of CC to morphisms of DD, preserving identities and composition. ¶Vocabulary (plain language) Preserve identity: F(idA)=idF(A)F(\\mathrm{id}_A) = \\mathrm{id}_{F(A)}. Preserve composition: F(g∘f)=F(g)∘F(f)F(g \\circ f) = F(g) \\circ F(f). ¶Symbols used F:C→DF:C \\to D: a functor from category CC to category DD. F(f)F(f): the image of a morphism ff under FF. ¶Intuition A functor is a translation that respects structure. It moves both things and processes between things, without changing how composition works.\n",
  "name": "Functors",
